25|$|In 1944, Anderson {{went to the}} Los Alamos National Laboratory, {{where he}} participated in using the Omega reactor to {{determine}} the critical mass of uranium-235. In preparation for the first <b>nuclear</b> <b>device</b> test on July 16, 1945, which was codenamed Trinity, Anderson, with his radiochemist colleagues, developed a method of determining the nuclear yield by collecting fission products at the detonation site. This technique was later perfected for nuclear yield determinations through the analysis of airborne fission products.|$|E
